, but the modifications of its properties by size effects and by interaction with the supporting material are still far from being well understood. In this communication we report XPS measurements on Au/Pt and Au/Re systems in a gold coverage range from submonolayer amounts to several monolayers, and the core level and 5d-band shifts calculated using local density functional method within the initial state approximation.
2. Experimental and computational details
The XPS measurements were carried out using ESCA 310 (Gammadata Scienta) and ESCA 3 Mk II (VG Scientific) spectrometers equipped with an Al Kα X-ray source and hemispherical electron analyser. The pressure of residual gases in the spectrometer chamber was below 108 Pa. High purity (99.99%) polycrystalline Pt and Re foils were cleaned by argon ion sputtering (E=6 keV, I=40 μA). The amounts of Au (99.99%) ranging from 0.01 to 18 equivalent monolayers (ML) were vapour deposited in situ, using calibrated cold trap evaporator (VG Scientific) with the substrate kept at room temperature. Both, sputtered and annealed (900 K) surfaces were used for deposition. For each surface coverage the spectra of Au 4f, Pt 4f, Re 4f and of valence electrons were measured at several different polar angles ranging from 10 to 90. The contribution of the gold deposit to the valence band photoemission was determined by subtracting a suitably attenuated spectrum of a clean substrate surface. The attenuation was determined from intensities of the Pt 4f (Re 4f) spectra by assuming that the spectra of valence electrons and Pt 4f (Re 4f) electrons are affected by the deposited gold to the same extent. Implicit in this procedure is the assumption that the shape of the Pt substrate spectrum is not significantly changed by the deposited gold.
In calculations the tight-binding linear muffin-tin-orbital scheme in the atomic-sphere-approximation (TB-LMTO-ASA)
[5]
was utilized within the local density-functional method. This is an essentially first-principles density-functional scheme with simplified treatment of charge between the atomic spheres (ASA). The supercell method was employed with periodically repeating metallic and vacuum slabs, respectively (7-layer ideal fcc (1 1 1) or hcp (0 0 0 1) slabs with 7-layer vacuum slabs above surfaces). Our theoretical analysis is based on properties of the d-electron states. We consider (1) the shifts and local densities of the 5d-electronic states, (2) core level shifts (CLS) of 4f electrons evaluated in the initial-state approximation
[6]
,
[7]
. For d-band systems, the accuracy of this approximation varies from rather accurate to a semi-quantitative guess. We considered epitaxial (1 × 1) Au overlayers corresponding to coverage θ=1 ML and a p(2 × 2) structure with θ=0.25 ML, and a (2 × 2) ordered-alloy Au3M and AuM3 (M=Pt, Re). Atoms M reside always in ideal lattice positions with experimental MM distances. The Au atoms reside in symmetric 3-fold positions above the surface. For Pt, fcc-like sites were considered, whereas for Re, both fcc- and hcp-like adsorption sites were studied. The two latter choices yield, however, almost the same results. The AuM (subsurface) distances were assessed from metallic-radii values. The atomic-radii Au-M misfit (45%) is in the range where epitaxial Au growth might be possible. Nevertheless, some kind of local expansion near Au atoms is likely
[8]
. Within cell of reasonably small dimensions, change of AuM (subsurface) can be considered but there is no effective possibility to change atomic separations within the surface plane.
3. Results and discussion
The Au 4f7/2 core electrons of gold deposited on Pt shift with increasing coverage to higher binding energies (
Fig. 1
); the CLS amounts 0.78 eV for 0.01 ML and 0.35 eV for 1 ML. More than 5 ML of Au are required to achieve the bulk value. The size of shifts does not depend on whether the sputtered or annealed Pt surface was used for deposition. Similar behaviour of Au 4f CLS has been reported
[9]
,
[10]
for Au deposited on Pt(1 0 0) surface and explained by island growth of Au and changing contribution of the Au atoms with three different coordinations to the measured spectra. In this interpretation, it was implicitly assumed that Au/Pt interface is abrupt without any intermixing. Our results thus demonstrate that CLS of Au 4f electrons do not depend on the Pt substrate surface structure. Let us to mention that the size of the measured shifts is close to that reported for AuPt bulk alloys
[11]
.
