Gold deposition induces rather small but measurable and reproducible shifts of the substrate Pt 4f spectra amounting to 0.07 eV for several monolayers of Au and normal emission. The magnitude of this shift was dependent on the take-off angle; it increased with decreasing take-off angle (defined from the sample surface) indicating thus presence of additional component in the spectra of Pt 4f electrons, which can be assigned to the Au/Pt interface alloy. Analogous shifts in the spectra of the Re 4f electrons have not been observed. Consequently, the results obtained seem to indicate that intermixing occurs at the Au/Pt interface in contrast to abrupt Au/Re interface.
The maximum on the dependence of Au 4f7/2 line FWHM on coverage is observed for both, Au/Pt and Au/Re (
