For θ(Au)=0.25, we find always large negative CLS and 5d-band shifts. This is not surprising since for Au atoms with very low coordination, the band-narrowing effects
[15]
prevail. Let us note that the above geometry is probably not very realistic since for very low coverages, the adatoms will adsorb preferably at defect sites such at steps that will increase their coordination. For deposition on Re, however, we find positive shifts which can become large as the number of Re neighbours of surface Au atoms grows. If a local lattice expansion at the compressed Au atoms were introduced, some additional Au band-narrowing would result. This means that the gold CLS's are probably somewhat more negative (less positive) in bimetallic systems than those calculated here. Besides that, in transition + noble metal systems the final core-hole screening becomes stronger with increase of the transition-metal concentration
[7]
. In other words, our Au CLS prediction underestimates the negative value (overestimates the positive value) probably most in cases of low Au concentration such as the AuM3 overlayer.
4. Conclusions
Angle resolved XPS study of Au deposited on Pt and Re sputtered or annealed surfaces was performed. The core level binding energy shifts and linewidths of the Au 4f core level as a function of surface Au coverage were measured and found independent on surface structure in the case of Pt substrate. The results point to the formation of Au/Pt alloy interface in early stages of Au deposition in contrast to abrupt Au/Re interface. The measured core level binding energy shifts are semi-quantitatively reproduced by theoretical calculations within the initial state approximation.


